The sudo su command allows you to run all future commands in the terminal as root, meaning that you will not need to write sudo for every command that requires it.
sudo pdbedit -L -v command can be used to check which accounts have been disabled using the smbpasswd utility.
A disabled account will usually have [D ] or [DISABLED ] or a flag that clearly indicates "disabled".


find netcat backdoor: 
ps aux | grep ncat 
ps aux | grep netcat

after finding the port, use the port number and write this command:
ps aux | grep PORTNUMBER
usually starts with /bin

use crontab -l command to find all cronjobs and use crontab -e to edit/delete cronjobs 
kill -9 PROCESSID command to end it

use sudo ss -tulnp to check open network ports

use systemctl list-units --type=service -- state=active to check running services and use sudo systemctl disable --now SERVICENAME to disable and stop the service.

use sudo passwd -e USERNAME to force password change at next login
